main event: Radar stations at Montauk, New York and Benson, Pennsylvania detected high-speed unidentified objects on September 20, 1957.
interesting points: The initial object was tracked by the radar at Montauk, reaching speeds up to 5,400 knots (over 6,200 mph).
The Benton radar station also detected two high-speed tracks, with one reaching speeds around 1,500 knots (over 1,700 mph).
The radar returns showed unusual characteristics, such as a 1.0 blip-scan ratio and rapid changes in size and intensity that are not typical of normal aircraft.
Weather conditions and equipment malfunctions were investigated as possible causes, but could not fully explain the radar observations.
While the report concludes the tracks were likely due to equipment issues, it states it is difficult to draw definitive conclusions about the nature of the objects.
location: Montauk, New York to Benson, Pennsylvania
